name: 3SUM
description:
Given an array 
    a
 of positive integers with length 
    n
, determine if
there exist three distinct indices 
    i
, 
    j
, 
    k
 such that 
    a_i
    + a_j + a_k
 ends in the digit 
    3
. Input The first line contains an
integer 
    t
 (
    1 
    ≤ t 
    ≤ 1000
) — the number of test cases. The
first line of each test case contains an integer 
    n
 (
    3 
    ≤ n 
    ≤
    2 
    · 10^5
) — the length of the array. The second line of each test
case contains 
    n
 integers 
    a_1, a_2, 
    …, a_n
 (
    1 
    ≤ a_i
    
    ≤ 10^9
) — the elements of the array. The sum of 
    n
 across all
test cases does not exceed 
    2 
    · 10^5
. Output Output 
    t
 lines,
each of which contains the answer to the corresponding test case. Output "YES"
if there exist three distinct indices 
    i
, 
    j
, 
    k
 satisfying the
constraints in the statement, and "NO" otherwise. You can output the answer in
any case (for example, the strings "yEs", "yes", "Yes" and "YES" will be
recognized as a positive answer). Example Input 6 4 20 22 19 84 4 1 11 1 2022
4 1100 1100 1100 1111 5 12 34 56 78 90 4 1 9 8 4 6 16 38 94 25 18 99 Output
YES YES NO NO YES YES Note In the first test case, you can select 
    i=1
,

    j=4
, 
    k=3
. Then 
    a_1 + a_4 + a_3 = 20 + 84 + 19 = 123
, which
ends in the digit 
    3
. In the second test case, you can select 
    i=1
,

    j=2
, 
    k=3
. Then 
    a_1 + a_2 + a_3 = 1 + 11 + 1 = 13
, which ends
in the digit 
    3
. In the third test case, it can be proven that no such

    i
, 
    j
, 
    k
 exist. Note that 
    i=4
, 
    j=4
, 
    k=4
 is
not a valid solution, since although 
    a_4 + a_4 + a_4 = 1111 + 1111 + 1111 =
    3333
, which ends in the digit 
    3
, the indices need to be distinct. In
the fourth test case, it can be proven that no such 
    i
, 
    j
, 
    k

exist. In the fifth test case, you can select 
    i=4
, 
    j=3
, 
    k=1
.
Then 
    a_4 + a_3 + a_1 = 4 + 8 + 1 = 13
, which ends in the digit 
    3
.
In the sixth test case, you can select 
    i=1
, 
    j=2
, 
    k=6
. Then

    a_1 + a_2 + a_6 = 16 + 38 + 99 = 153
, which ends in the digit 
    3
.
